 Example of Moiré effect. Each frame is a step of rotation.
 The Moiré effect on random dots was developed to illustrate the effect of local correlations on visual perception by Leon Glass (Glass, 1969). Glass first demonstrated the effect using a copy machine and copying a piece of paper with random noise. Local linear patterns are observed for small rotations.
